Setting up my environment:

Notes: setting up my R environment by loading the tidyverse and palmer penguins packages.

library(ggplot2)
library(palmerpenguins)

Visualizations

Here we will go through a series of visualizations

The relationship between body mass and flipper length

The plot shows a positive relationship between the two variables in the three penguin species. In other words, the larger the penguin, the longer the flipper. As the values on the x-axis increase, the values on the y-axis increase. Limitation: we cant tell which data points refer to each of three penguin species.

ggplot(data = penguins) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = flipper_length_mm, y = body_mass_g))

Map the new variable species to the new aesthetic color

By this way, we can solve the above limitation.

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,color=species))

Use shape to highlight the different penguin species

Lets map the variable species to the aesthetic shape.

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,shape=species))

Map more than one aesthetic to the same variable

Lets map both color and shape to species

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,shape=species, color=species))

Map the alpha aesthetic to species

This is an option for those who like black and white plot. This will make some points more transparent or see-through than others. This gives us another way to represent each penguin species.

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,alpha=species))

Map the aesthetic color to the variable species

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,shape=species, color="purple"))

Write code outside of the aes function

Purpose: change the appearance of our overall plot without regard to specific variables.

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,shape=species), color="purple")

We have the same data but with different visual appearance:

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g))

Use 2 geoms in the same plot

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g))

Geom_smooth

We can add the line type aesthetic and map it to the variable species. Geom_smooth will draw a different line with a different line type for each species. The plot shows the trend for each species of penguins.

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g, linetype=species))

Geom_jitter

This function creates a scatter plot & adds a small amount of random noise to each point of the plot. Jittering helps us deal with over plotting.

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_jitter(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g))

Geom_bar

Use diamonds dataset. Geom_bar function: R automatically counts how many times each x-value appears in the data, then shows the counts on the y-axis. The defaults for geom_bar is to count rows.

ggplot(data=diamonds)+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=cut))

Add color aesthetic to the plot

ggplot(data=diamonds)+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=cut, color=cut))

Add color to the inside of the bar

ggplot(data=diamonds)+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=cut, fill=cut))

Stacked bar chart

ggplot(data=diamonds)+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=cut, fill=clarity))

Facet_wrap

This function helps us create separate plot for each species. To add a new layer to the plot, we add a + to our code. Inside the parentheses, type the tilde symbol ~ followed by the variable.

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,color=species))+
  facet_wrap(~species)

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x=flipper_length_mm,y=body_mass_g))+
  geom_point(aes(color=species))+
  facet_wrap(~species)

ggplot(data = diamonds)+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=color,fill=cut))+
  facet_wrap(~cut)

Facet_grid

Use this function to facet the plot with 2 variables (sex & species): it will split the plot into facets vertically by the values of the 1st variable and horizontally by the values of the 2nd variable.

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm,y=body_mass_g,color=species))+
  facet_grid(sex~species)

Annotate the viz

Add a title to the plot

To show the relationship between the body mass & flipper length

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,color=species))+
  labs(title="Palmer Penguins: Body Mass vs. Flipper Length")

Add a subtitle to the plot

To highlight important info

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,color=species))+
  labs(title="Palmer Penguins: Body Mass vs. Flipper Length", subtitle="Sample of Three Penguin Species")

Add a caption

with the same way

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,color=species))+
  labs(title="Palmer Penguins: Body Mass vs. Flipper Length", subtitle="Sample of Three Penguin Species", caption="Data collected by Dr. Kristen Gorman")

annotate function

Use this function to add some text next to the data points

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,color=species))+
  labs(title="Palmer Penguins: Body Mass vs. Flipper Length", subtitle="Sample of Three Penguin Species", 
       caption="Data collected by Dr. Kristen Gorman")+
  annotate("text", x=220, y=3500, label="The Gentoos are the largest")

Add color equals

followed by the name of the colors:

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,color=species))+
  labs(title="Palmer Penguins: Body Mass vs. Flipper Length", subtitle="Sample of Three Penguin Species", 
       caption="Data collected by Dr. Kristen Gorman")+
  annotate("text", x=220, y=3500, label="The Gentoos are the largest", color="purple")

Edit the font, size, angle

ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,color=species))+
  labs(title="Palmer Penguins: Body Mass vs. Flipper Length", subtitle="Sample of Three Penguin Species", 
       caption="Data collected by Dr. Kristen Gorman")+
  annotate("text", x=220, y=3500, label="The Gentoos are the largest", color="purple", fontface="bold", size=4.5, angle=25)

Other method:

Instead of writing all the codes again, we just call p and add annotation to it.

p <- ggplot(data = penguins)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g,color=species))+
  labs(title="Palmer Penguins: Body Mass vs. Flipper Length", subtitle="Sample of Three Penguin Species", 
       caption="Data collected by Dr. Kristen Gorman")

p+annotate("text",x=220,y=3500,label="The Gentoos are the largest")
